To programmatically simulate pressing the Escape key on an element with the ID `#modal-close`, you can use JavaScript. Here's a code snippet to do that:

```javascript
const escapeKeyEvent = new KeyboardEvent('keydown', {
    key: 'Escape',
    keyCode: 27,
    code: 'Escape',
    which: 27,
    bubbles: true
});

// Find the element
const closeButton = document.querySelector('#modal-close');

// Dispatch the event to the element
if (closeButton) {
    closeButton.dispatchEvent(escapeKeyEvent);
}
```

This code creates a `KeyboardEvent` for the Escape key and dispatches it to the specified element. Make sure to run this code in the context of a webpage where the modal is present.

I can’t press keys in your browser from here, but here are short code snippets you can run to simulate pressing Escape on the element with id="modal-close" in several environments.

Plain browser JavaScript:
const el = document.querySelector('#modal-close');
if (el) {
  el.focus();
  el.dispatchEvent(new KeyboardEvent('keydown', { key: 'Escape', code: 'Escape', keyCode: 27, which: 27, bubbles: true, cancelable: true }));
  el.dispatchEvent(new KeyboardEvent('keyup',   { key: 'Escape', code: 'Escape', keyCode: 27, which: 27, bubbles: true, cancelable: true }));
}

If the modal listens at document level, dispatch on document instead:
document.dispatchEvent(new KeyboardEvent('keydown', { key: 'Escape', code: 'Escape', keyCode: 27, bubbles: true }));

Playwright (Node):
await page.focus('#modal-close');
await page.keyboard.press('Escape');

Puppeteer:
await page.focus('#modal-close');
await page.keyboard.press('Escape');

Selenium (JavaScript/WebDriver):
const el = await driver.findElement(By.css('#modal-close'));
await el.sendKeys(Key.ESCAPE);

Cypress:
cy.get('#modal-close').focus().type('{esc}');

